value.value: The long-term fluctuations in temperature, precipitation, wind, and all other aspects of the Earth's climate. External processes, such as solar-irradiance variations, variations of the Earth's orbital parameters (eccentricity, precession, and inclination), lithosphere motions, and volcanic activity, are factors in climatic variation. Internal variations of the climate system, e.g., changes in the abundance of greenhouse gases, also may produce fluctuations of sufficient magnitude and variability to explain observed climate change through the feedback processes interrelating the components of the climate system.

definition.value: Definition vebatim from GEMET. Will need to be refined. Further, distinction between "climate change" and (one or many) "climate change process" will need to be discussed. Fluctuations are not processes, per se.
Acidification of an aquatic environment is a process whereby the pH of an aquatic environment, biome, or water body is lowered.
Ocean acidification is a process during which the pH of a sea or ocean is lowered.
On Earth, the major cause of ocean acidification is the update of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.

value.value: A chonolith is an igneous rock intrusion of irregular shape with a demonstrable base, absent in other types of irregularly-shaped intrusions.

definition.value: A process which consists of all aerobic respiration processes instantiated in an ecosystem.

value.value: A volcanic eruption is a process during which lava, tephra (ash, lapilli, volcanic bombs and blocks), and assorted gases are expelled from a volcanic vent or fissure.
A landmass which is part of a planet.

Outer space is a hard vacuum containing a low density of particles, predominantly a plasma of hydrogen and helium as well as electromagnetic radiation, magnetic fields, neutrinos, dust and cosmic rays that exists between celestial bodies.
A planetary crust is the outermost solid shell of a rocky planet or natural satellite, which is chemically distinct from the underlying mantle.

definition.value: This class is meant to be applicable accross planets. Earth's crust would be an instance.

A planetary structural layer is laminar part of a terrestrial planet or other rocky body large enough to have differentiation by density. Planetary layers have differing physicochemical properties and composition.

value.value: A planetary mantle is a planetary layer which is an interior part of a terrestrial planet or other rocky body large enough to have differentiation by density.

definition.value: This class is meant to be applicable accross planets. Earth's mantle would be an instance.

value.value: A planetary core is the innermost structural layer or layers of a planet. The core may be entirely liquid, entirely solid, or have both liquid and solid parts.

definition.value: "Not to be confused with planetary core in the core accretion theory, referring to a central accretionary body surrounded by a halo of dust and gas which serves to trap debris and increase the rate of accretion.." WIkipedia:Planetary_core. This class is meant to be applicable accross planets. Earth's core would be an instance. The "layer" aspect of cores may be problematic.
Needs a general definition that holds for Earth as well as other planets.
Needs a general definition that holds for Earth as well as other planets.
A liquid planetary core is a planetary core which is primarily composed of liquid material.
A solid planetary core is a planetary core which is primarily composed of solid material.

value.value: A lithosphere is the outermost shell of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite that is defined by its rigid mechanical properties.

definition.value: Earth's lithosphere includes the crust and uppermost mantle.

value.value: An asthenosphere is a layer of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite which is highly viscous, mechanically weak, and ductilely deforming.

Magma is a mixture of molten or semi-molten rock, volatiles, and solids that is found beneath the uppermost solid layer of a planetary body. Besides molten rock, magma may also contain suspended crystals, dissolved gas and sometimes gas bubbles.

A trench is a type of excavation or depression in the ground that is generally deeper than it is wide (as opposed to a wider gully or ditch), and narrow compared to its length (as opposed to a simple hole).

definition.value: A channel of a watercourse which contains a stream.
An ocean strait is a strait which connects two oceans.
A stream channel which contains a river.

value.value: A slum is a heavily populated urban informal settlement with substandard housing in which households lack any one of the following: access to improved water, access to improved sanitation, sufficient-living area, durability of housing, or security of tenure.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.value: Definition linked to a UN Habitat report entitled "What are slums and why do they exist?" as well as sources from the MDGs and Communitas.

value.value: An undersea trough is a trough which is below a marine water body.

An explosive eruption is a volcanic process in which pressurised magma is violently expelled and froths into volcanic ash. Explosive eruptions can eject a cloud of rocks, dust, gas, and pyroclastic material  which may then collapse, creating a pyroclastic flow of hot volcanic matter.
An effusive eruption is a volcanic eruption during which lava flows onto the ground.
A process whereby rising magma cools and solidifies without reaching the surface. Instead, the cooled and solidified igneous mass crystallises within the crust to form an igneous intrusion.

definition.value: A settlement with a high density of buildings and inhabitants.
The thresholds for what makes a settlment "dense" can be determined as needed. If there is a specific threshold that should be added to ENVO, please make a new class request.

value.value: An igneous intrusion is a mass of rock and minerals formed when magma cools, solidifies, and undergoes fractional crystallisation without reaching the surface.

definition.value: "Intrusion" can refer to the solidified mass or the molten rock.

value.value: Tephra is fragmental material produced by a volcanic eruption regardless of composition, fragment size or emplacement mechanism.
Tuff is a type of rock made of volcanic ash ejected from a vent during a volcanic eruption.
Scoria is a highly vesicular, dark colored volcanic rock that may or may not contain crystals.

definition.value: Scoria differs from pumice in having larger vesicles, thicker vesicle walls and being dark colored and denser.

value.value: Pumice is a volcanic rock that consists of highly vesicular rough textured volcanic glass, which may or may not contain crystals.

definition.value: Scoria differs from pumice in having larger vesicles, thicker vesicle walls and being dark colored and denser.
A cone that is composed of consolidated volcanic ash.
A role that is realized in some process wherein the bearer is discarded or not utilized further.

value.value: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of water in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.

definition.value: According to the NLCD 2011, areas of open water generally have less than 25% cover of vegetation or soil. A specific threshold is not asserted in this definition.

value.value: A geological fracture is any separation in a geologic formation, such as a joint or a fault that divides a mass of rock into two or more pieces.

definition.value: A geological fault is a planar fracture or discontinuity in a volume of rock, across which there has been significant displacement as a result of rock mass movement.
The relationship between faults and active plate boundaries must be further developed, as there is some overlap.

An active fault is a fault that is likely to become the source of another earthquake sometime in the future. Geologists commonly consider faults to be active if there has been movement observed or evidence of seismic activity during the last 10,000 years.
A vein is a geological fracture which is filled with minerals precipitated out of an aqueous solution.

value.value: A sheet of rock that formed in a fracture in a pre-existing rock body.

definition.value: A joint is a geological fracture which has no measureable shear displacement
A geological fracture across which shear displacement has occurred
Sounds like this should be populated by inference.

A microfracture is a small fracture which is found in a portion of solid material along which further fracturing tends to occur. Microfractures are considered imperfections which to pre-exist any fractures formed by the application of stress to a material.

value.value: A fiat part of an atmosphere which is defined as a vertical, three-dimensional pillar extending from a unit area on a planetary surface and bounded by the top of the atmosphere.

definition.value: Once defined, an atmospheric column can be used to quantify an atmospheric parameter such as pressure, ozone or precipitable water.
Contaminated air is air which has sufficient concentrations of environmental pollutants such that it may adversely affect a given ecosystem.

value.value: An earthquake is a process during which energy is released in an astronomical body's crust, causing the displacement of crustal parts and the generation of seismic waves.

definition.value: Elastic strain, gravity, chemical reactions, or even the motion of massive bodies can produce earthquakes.

value.value: An earthquake caused by the sudden release of energy accumulated in an astronomical body's crust, as the elastic strain placed on constituent rock masses causes them to fracture.
